# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chaplino-dialect
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chaplino-dialect/a-cyrillic] The Cyrillic letter А was derived directly from the Greek letter Alpha (Α α).
[src:chaplino-dialect/a-cyrillic] In the Early Cyrillic alphabet its name was азъ (azǔ), meaning the personal pronoun "I".
[src:chaplino-dialect/a-cyrillic] In the Cyrillic numeral system, the Cyrillic letter А has a value of 1.
[src:chaplino-dialect/a-cyrillic] Throughout history, the Cyrillic letter А has had various shapes, but today is standardized on one that looks exactly like the Latin letter A, including the italic and lower case forms.
[src:chaplino-dialect/a-cyrillic] In most languages that use the Cyrillic alphabet – such as Bulgarian, Ukrainian, Belarusian, Russian, Rusyn, Serbian, Macedonian and Montenegrin – the Cyrillic letter А represents the open central unrounded vowel /a/.
[src:chaplino-dialect/a-cyrillic] In Ingush and Chechen, the Cyrillic letter А represents both the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/ when stressed and the mid-central vowel /ə/ when unstressed.
[src:chaplino-dialect/a-cyrillic] In Turkic languages that use the Cyrillic script it represents the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/, with the exception of Volga Tatar, in which it represents the open back rounded vowel /ɒ/, and Uzbek, in which it represents the near-open front unrounded vowel /æ/.
[src:chaplino-dialect/a-cyrillic] In languages that contrast vowel length the letter can be written as double vowel.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Various sources estimate there are fewer than 100 to 150 remaining active Aleut speakers.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Because of this, Eastern and Atkan Aleut are classified as "critically endangered and extinct" and have an Expanded Graded Intergenerational Disruption Scale (EGIDS) rating of 7.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The task of revitalizing Aleut has largely been left to local government and community organizations.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The overwhelming majority of schools in the historically Aleut-speaking regions lack any language/culture courses in their curriculum, and those that do fail to produce fluent or even proficient speakers.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The Eskimo and Aleut peoples were part of a migration from Asia across Beringia, the Bering land bridge between 4,000 and 6,000 years ago.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] During this period, the Proto-Eskimo-Aleut language was spoken, which broke up around 2000 BC.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Differentiation of the two branches is thought to have happened in Alaska because of the linguistic diversity found in the Eskimo languages of Alaska relative to the entire geographic area where Eskimo languages are spoken (eastward through Canada to Greenland).
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] After the split between the two branches, their development is thought to have occurred in relative isolation.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Evidence suggests a culture associated with Aleut speakers on the Eastern Aleutian Islands as early as 4,000 years ago, followed by a gradual expansion westward over the next 1,500 years to the Near Islands.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Another westward expansion may have occurred about 1,000 years ago, which may explain the lack of obvious diversification among the Aleut dialects, with Eastern Aleut features having spread westward.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] This second westward expansion is characterized as a period of cultural affinity with southeastern Alaska and the Pacific Northwest Coast, which may explain linguistic features that Aleut shares with neighboring non-Eskimo languages, such as rules of plural formation.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Due to colonization by Russian colonizers and traders in the 18th and 19th centuries, Aleut has a large portion of Russian loanwords.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] However, they do not affect the basic vocabulary and thus do not suggest undue influence on the language.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In March 2021, the last native speaker of the Bering dialect, Vera Timoshenko, died aged 93 in Nikolskoye, Bering Island, Kamchatka.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Within the Eastern group are the dialects of the Alaskan Peninsula, Unalaska, Belkofski, Akutan, the Pribilof Islands, Kashega and Nikolski.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The Pribilof dialect has more living speakers than any other dialect of Aleut.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The Atkan grouping comprises the dialects of Atka and Bering Island.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Attuan was a distinct dialect showing influence from both Atkan and Eastern Aleut.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Copper Island Aleut (also called Medny Aleut) was a Russian-Attuan mixed language (Copper Island (Russian: Медный, *Medny*, *Mednyj*) having been settled by Attuans).
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Despite the name, after 1969 Copper Island Aleut was spoken only on Bering Island, as Copper Islanders were evacuated there.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] After the death of the last native speaker in 2022, it became extinct.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] All dialects show lexical influence from Russian; Copper Island Aleut has also adopted many Russian inflectional endings.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The largest number of Russian loanwords can be seen in the Bering Aleut.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The consonant phonemes of the various Aleut dialects are represented below.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Each cell indicates the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA) representation of the phoneme; consonants existing only in loanwords are in parentheses.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Some phonemes are unique to specific dialects of Aleut.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The palato-alveolar affricate /tʃ/ and uvular stop /q/ are pronounced with strong aspiration.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Attuan labial fricative /v/ is pronounced voiced or devoiced.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Voiceless approximants and devoiced nasals are preaspirated.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The preaspiration of approximants causes very little friction and may be pronounced more as a breathy voice.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The preaspiration of devoiced nasals starts with a voiceless airstream through the nose and may end voiced before a vowel.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The preaspiration feature is represented orthographically with an ⟨h⟩ preceding the given sound.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] For example, a devoiced, preaspirated labial nasal would be written ⟨hm⟩.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Voiced approximants and nasals may be partly devoiced in contact with a voiceless consonant and at the end of a word.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The voiceless glottal approximant /h/ functions as an initial aspiration before a vowel.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In Atkan and Attuan, the prevocalic /h/ aspiration contrasts with an audible but not written glottal stop initiation of the vowel.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Compare *halal* ('to turn the head') and *alal* ('to need').
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] This contrast has been lost in Eastern Aleut.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Modern Eastern Aleut has a much simpler consonant inventory because the voice contrasts among nasals, sibilants and approximants have been lost.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Consonants listed in the dental column have varied places of articulation.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The stop, nasal, and lateral dentals commonly have a laminal articulation.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The voiced dental fricative is pronounced interdentally.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The pronunciation of the sibilant /s/ varies from an alveolar articulation to a retracted articulation like a palato-alveolar consonant.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] There is no contrast between /s/ and /ʃ/ in Aleut.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Many Aleut speakers experience difficulties with this distinction while learning English.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Aleut has a basic three-vowel system including the high front /i/, low /a/, and high back /u/.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Aleut vowels contrast with their long counterparts /iː/, /aː/, and /uː/.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Notably, Aleut /u/ is pronounced slightly lower than /i/ in the vowel space.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The long vowel /aː/ is pronounced retracted in the vowel space creating a significant distinction relative to the vowel length of /a/.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The two high vowels are pronounced with the same vowel quality regardless of vowel length.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In contact with a uvular, /i/ is lowered to [e], /a/ is backed to [ɑ], and /u/ is lowered to [o].
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In contact with a coronal, /a/ is raised to [e] or [ɛ], and /u/ is fronted to [ʉ].
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The mid-vowels [ɔ] and [ɛ] occur only in family names like *Nevzorof* and very recently introduced Russian loanwords.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] An Aleut word may contain one to about a dozen syllables, all syllables with a vocalic nucleus.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In Atkan and Attuan, there is a word-final CC due to apocopation.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] There also exist word initial CCC in loanwords.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] A word may begin or end in a vowel, both short and long, with few exceptions.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Due to apocopation, short /u/ is not found in the final position.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The same is true for short /i/, except in some obsolete suffixes, such as *-chi* 'your' (pl.) which is realized as *-chin* and *-chix* in modern Eastern and Atkan Aleut.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Vowels within a word are separated by at least one consonant.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Words begin with any consonant except /θ/ and preaspirated consonants (with the exception of the preaspirated /ŋ̊/ in Atkan Aleut).
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Only in loanwords do /v/, /z/, and the borrowed consonants (*p, b, f, d, g, ɹ/ɾ)* appear word-initially.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Intervocalic CC can occur in normal structure or as the result of syncopation.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In CC clusters of two voiced continuants, there is often a short transitional vowel.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] For example, *qilĝix̂* 'umbilical cord' is pronounced [-liĝ-] similar to *qiliĝi-n* 'brain'.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Almost all possible combinations of coronal and postlingual consonants are attested.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The combination of two postlingual or two coronal consonants is rare, but attested, such as *hux̂xix* 'rain pants', *aliĝngix̂* 'wolf', *asliming* 'fit for me', *iistalix* 'to say; to tell; to call'.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In CCC clusters, the middle consonant is either /t/, /tʃ/, /s/.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] For example, *taxtxix̂* 'pulse', *huxsx̂ilix* 'to wrap up', *chamchxix̂* 'short fishline'.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The most common single consonants to appear word-final are /x/, /χ/, /m/, /n/, /ŋ/, and /j/.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Through apocopation, word-final single consonants /l/ and /s/ occur, and word-final consonant clusters ending with /t/ or /s/.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The details of the extensive syncopation characteristic of the Eastern Aleut dialect are described below.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In the examples, the syncopated vowel will be shown in parentheses.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] A word medial short vowel may be syncopated between single consonants, except after an initial open short syllable and/or before a final open short syllable.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] For example, *ìx̂am(a)nákux̂* 'it is good' and *alqut(a)maan* 'what for?'.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The syncopation often creates consonant clusters beyond those prescribed by the general rules of Aleut phonotactics.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In some frequently encountered syncopated forms, which otherwise result in irregular three consonant clusters, the middle uvular fricative is deleted along with the preceding vowel.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] For example, *(h)iis(ax̂)talix* 'saying' and *(h)iil(ax̂)talix* 'being said'.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] At slower speeds of speech, the syncopation may not be realized.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Compare *txin saakutikux̂txin* 'you are getting skinny' beside *ting saak(u)tikuqing* 'I am getting skinny'.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Aleut stress is indeterminate and often difficult to define.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Stress varies based on the relation to the beginning or end of the word form, the length of the vowels, the sonority of the consonants, open- or closeness of the syllables, or the number of syllables in sentential rhythm and intonation.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Stress affects the length of both vowels and consonants.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Stress underlies the distinctive syncopation characteristics of Eastern Aleut.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In the following discussion, the acute accent (á) indicates the stronger stress and the grave accent (à) indicates the weaker.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In Eastern Aleut, stronger stress tends to fall on the penultimate syllable if it is short (has a short vowel), or on the last syllable if it is long (has a long vowel).
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The weaker stress commonly falls on the first syllable.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] For example, *úlax̂* 'house', *tùnúnax̂* 'talked', *tùnulákan* 'without talking', *ìnaqáam* 'he himself'.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Eastern Aleut words with more than two syllables exhibit a wider variety of stress patterns.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Stress may be attracted to another syllable by a long vowel or relatively sonorant consonant, or by a closed syllable.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] It is possible the stress can be determined by rhythmic factors so that one word will have different stress in different contexts, such as *áĝadax̂* compared to *àĝádax̂*, both meaning 'arrow'.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In Atkan and Attuan Aleut, stronger stress more commonly falls on the first syllable.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] However, long vowels, sonorants, etc. have similar effects on stress as in Eastern Aleut.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] For example, *qánáang* 'how many' vs *qánang* 'where'; *ùĝálux̂* 'spear' vs *álaĝux̂* 'sea'.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Stress may also be expressive, as with exclamations or polite requests.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Stronger stress falls on the last syllable and is accompanied by a lengthening of a short vowel.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] For example, *kúufyax̂ àqakúx̂!* 'coffee is coming'.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] There is a similar structure for polite requests: *qadá* 'please eat!' vs *qáda* 'eat'.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Under ordinary strong stress, a short syllable tends to be lengthened, either by lengthening the vowel or geminating the following single consonant.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Lengthening of the vowel is most common in Eastern, but is found in Atkan before a voiced consonant.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In all dialects gemination is common between an initial stressed syllable with a short vowel and a following stressed syllable.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] For example, *ìláan* 'from him' pronounced [-ll-] and *làkáayax̂* 'a boy' pronounced [-kk-].
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The following descriptions involve phonological processes that occur in connected speech.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Word-final velar and uvular fricatives are voiceless when followed by a word-initial voiceless consonant and are voiced when followed by a word-initial voiced consonant or a vowel.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Word-final nasals /m/ and /n/ are frequently deleted before an initial consonant other than /h/.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] For example, *tana(m) kugan* 'on the ground' and *ula(m) naga* 'the interior of the house'.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In Eastern Aleut, the final vowel may be elided before or contracted with the initial vowel of the following word, as in *aamg(ii) iĝanalix* 'he is bleeding awfully'.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In Atkan, the final syllable of a word form may be clipped off in fast speech.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] This is even frequent at slow speed in certain constructions with auxiliary verbs.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The historic Aleut (Cyrillic) alphabet found in both Alaska and Russia has the standard pre-1918 Russian orthography as its basis, although a number of Russian letters were used only in loanwords.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In addition, the extended Cyrillic letters г̑ (г with inverted breve), ҟ, ҥ, ў, х̑ (х with inverted breve) were used to represent distinctly Aleut sounds.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] A total of 24+ letters were used to represent distinctly Aleut words, including 6 vowels (а, и, й, у, ю, я) and 16 consonants (г, г̑, д, з, к, ԟ, л, м, н, ҥ, с, т, ў, х, х̑, ч).
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The letter ӄ has replaced the letter ԟ (Aleut Ka) for the voiceless uvular plosive /q/ in modern Aleut Cyrillic publications.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Open word classes in Aleut include nouns and verbs, both derived from stems with suffixes.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Many stems are ambivalent, being both nominal and verbal (see § Derivation).
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] There are no adjectives other than verbal nouns and participles.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Other word classes include pronouns, contrastives, quantifiers, numerals, positional nouns, demonstratives, and interrogatives.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The anaphoric third person refers to a proceeding term, specified by being marked in the relative case or from context.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] For example, *tayaĝu-m ula-a* 'the man's house' and *ula-a* 'his house'.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] As free forms, the pronouns are used primarily as an object, like fully specified nouns.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] As enclitics they function as subject markers.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Positional nouns indicate positional, directional, or some more abstract relation to a definite referent (a person or proceeding noun in relative case).
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Positional nouns have possessive suffixes but no inherent number.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Unlike ordinary nouns, positional nouns have two adverbial cases: locative and/or ablative.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The most important stem *i-*, called the dative, has only a locative form (largely irregular) meaning 'to, at, for-'.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Most are used in absolutive case, as in *ula-m agal-a agikux̂* 'he passed behind the house'.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] They can also be used in the relative case, as in *laavki-m agal-a-n ula-a* 'the house behind the store'.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The numeral system is decimal with *hatix̂* 'ten' and *sisax̂* 'hundred' as the basic higher terms.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The higher tens numerals are derived through multiplication (e.g.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The multiplicative numerals are derived with the suffix *-di-m* on the base numeral followed by *hatix̂* 'ten'.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Verbs differ from nouns morphologically by having mood/tense suffixes.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Like nominal stems, verb stems may end in a short vowel or consonant.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Many stems ending in a consonant had auxiliary vowels which have largely become part of the stem itself.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Negation is sometimes suffixal, preceding or combining with the mood/tense suffix.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In some cases the negation will be followed by the enclitic subject pronoun.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] There are 570 derivational suffixes (postbases) including many composite ones, but about two thirds are found only in a small number of words.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] There are approximately 175 more common suffixes, considerably less than the Eskimo branch of the family.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] A postbase may be nominal or verbal, yielding nouns derived from nouns or verbs, or verbs derived from verbs or nouns, or from nominal phrases.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Many stems are ambivalent, being either nominal or verbal and even some derivatives can be ambivalent.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Difficulties distinguishing between nominal and verbal parts of speech arise because the parts of speech in Aleut are not easy to distinguish.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] A verbal stem may be used as a verbal predicate, and quite often as a noun.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The verbal use of nouns is also very common.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The derivational suffixes may combine in strings of up to about six components, some belonging together to form composites.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In sequences, each successive suffix often modifies the preceding string.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The majority of derivatives have a single stem that occurs also without the suffixes in question.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] While some stems are bound, only occurring with some derivational suffix.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] For example, compare *iĝa-t-* 'to scare, frighten' *iĝa-x̂ta-* 'to fear, be afraid of' *iĝa-na-* 'to be terrible, frightening'.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Most Aleut words can be classified as nouns or verbs.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Notions which in English are expressed by means of adjectives and adverbs are generally expressed in Aleut using verbs or postbases (derivational suffixes).
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Aleut's canonical word order is subject–object–verb (SOV).
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Nouns are obligatorily marked for grammatical number (singular, dual, or plural) and for absolutive case or relative case (some researchers, notably Anna Berge, dispute both the characterization of this feature as "case" and the names *absolutive* and *relative*.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] This approach to Aleut nouns comes from Eskimo linguistics, but these terms can be misleading when applied to Aleut).
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The absolutive form is the default form, while the relative form communicates a relationship (such as possessive or contrastive) between the noun and another member of the sentence, possibly one that has been omitted.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Absolutive and relative are identical in most combinations of person and number.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The verbal predicate of a simple sentence of the final clause of a complex sentence carries the temporal and modal marking in relation to the speech act.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Verbs of non-final clauses are marked in relation to the following clause.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] A complex sentence may contain an unlimited number of clauses.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Simple sentences may include a subject or no subject.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The predicate may be a verb with no complement, a predicate noun with a copula, or a verb with a preceding direct object in the absolutive case and/or an oblique term or local complement.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The number of arguments may be increased or decreased by verbal derivative suffixes.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Arguments of a clause may be explicitly specified or anaphoric.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The verb of a simple sentence or final clause may have a nominal subject in the absolutive case or a first-/second-person subject marker.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Positional nouns are a special, closed set of nouns which may take the locative or ablative noun cases; in these cases they behave essentially as postpositions.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Verbs are inflected for mood and, if finite, for person and number.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] When more than one piece of information is omitted, the verb agrees with the element whose grammatical number is greatest.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Although Aleut derives from the same parent language as the Eskimo languages, the two language groups (Aleut and Eskimo) have evolved in distinct ways, resulting in significant typological differences.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Aleut inflectional morphology is greatly reduced from the system that must have been present in Proto-Eskimo–Aleut, and where the Eskimo languages mark a verb's arguments morphologically, Aleut relies more heavily on a fixed word order.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Unlike the Eskimo languages, Aleut is not an ergative-absolutive language.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Subjects and objects in Aleut are not marked differently depending on the transitivity of the verb (i.e. whether the verb is transitive or intransitive); by default, both are marked with a so-called absolutive noun ending.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] However, if an understood complement (which may either be a complement of the verb or of some other element in the sentence) is absent, the verb takes an "anaphoric" marking and the subject noun takes a "relative" noun ending.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The first contact of people from the Eastern Hemisphere with the Aleut language occurred in 1741, as Vitus Bering's expedition picked up place names and the names of the Aleut people they met.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The first recording of the Aleut language in lexicon form appeared in a word list of the Unalaskan dialect compiled by Captain James King on Cook's voyage in 1778.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] At that time the Imperial Academy of Sciences in Saint Petersburg became interested in the Aleut language upon hearing of Russian expeditions for trading.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In Catherine the Great's project to compile a giant comparative dictionary on all the languages spoken in what was the spread of the Russian empire at that time, she hired Peter Simon Pallas to conduct the fieldwork that would collect linguistic information on Aleut.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] During an expedition from 1791 to 1792, Carl Heinrich Merck and Michael Rohbeck collected several word lists and conducted a census of the male population that included prebaptismal Aleut names.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Explorer Yuriy Feodorovich Lisyansky compiled several word lists. in 1804 and 1805, the czar's plenipotentiary, Nikolai Petrovich Rezanov collected some more.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Johann Christoph Adelung and Johann Severin Vater published their *Mithridates oder allgemeine Sprachkunde 1806–1817*, which included Aleut among the languages it catalogued, similar to Catherine the Great's dictionary project.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] It was not until 1819 that the first professional linguist, the Dane Rasmus Rask, studied Aleut.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] He collected words and paradigms from two speakers of Eastern Aleut dialects living in Saint Petersburg.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In 1824 came the man who would revolutionize Aleut as a literary language.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Ioann Veniaminov, a Russian Orthodox priest who would later become a saint, arrived at Unalaska studying Unalaskan Aleut.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] He created an orthography for this language (using the Cyrillic alphabet; the Roman alphabet would come later), translated the Gospel according to St.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Matthew and several other religious works into Aleut, and published a grammar of Eastern Aleut in 1846.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The religious works were translated with the help of Veniaminov's friends Ivan Pan'kov (chief of Tigalda) and Iakov Netsvetov (the priest of Atka), both of whom were native Aleut speakers.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Netsvetov also wrote a dictionary of Atkan Aleut.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] After Veniaminov's works were published, several religious figures took interest in studying and recording Aleut, which would help these Russian Orthodox clerics in their missionary work.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Father Innocent Shayashnikov did much work in the Eastern Fox-Island dialect translating a Catechism, all four Gospels and Acts of Apostles from the New Testament, and an original composition in Aleut entitled: "Short Rule for a Pious Life".
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Most of these were published in 1902, although written years earlier in the 1860s and 1870s.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Father Lavrentii Salamatov produced a Catechism, and translations of three of the four Gospels (St.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Of Father Lavrentii's work, the Gospel of St.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Mark was published in a revised orthography (1959), and in its original, bilingual Russian-Aleut format (2007), together with his Catechism for the youth of Atka Island (2007).
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] John was also electronically published (2008), along with the Gospel of St.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Luke (2009) in the original bilingual format, completing the set of Fr.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The first Frenchman to record Aleut was Alphonse Pinart, in 1871, shortly after the United States purchase of Alaska.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] A French-Aleut grammar was also produced by Victor Henry, titled *Esquisse d'une grammaire raisonnee de la langue aleoute d'apres la grammaire et le vocabulaire de Ivan Veniaminov* (Paris, 1879).
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Turner began work on collecting words for a word list.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Benedykt Dybowski, a Pole, began taking word lists from the dialects of the Commander Islands in 1881, while Nikolai Vasilyevich Slyunin, a Russian doctor, did the same in 1892.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] From 1909 to 1910, the ethnologist Waldemar Jochelson traveled to the Aleut communities of Unalaska, Atka, Attu and Nikolski.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] He spent nineteen months there doing fieldwork.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Jochelson collected his ethnographic work with the help of two Unalaskan speakers, Aleksey Yachmenev and Leontiy Sivtsov.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] He recorded many Aleut stories, folklore and myth, and had many of them not only written down but also recorded in audio.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Jochelson discovered much vocabulary and grammar when he was there, adding to the scientific knowledge of the Aleut language.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In the 1930s, two native Aleuts wrote down works that are considered breakthroughs in the use of Aleut as a literary language.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Ermeloff wrote down a literary account of a shipwreck in his native language, while Ardelion G.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Ermeloff kept a diary in Aleut during the decade.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] At the same time, linguist Melville Jacobs picked up several new texts from Sergey Golley, an Atkan speaker who was hospitalized at the time.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Harrington furthered research into the Pribilof Island dialect on St.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Paul Island in 1941, collecting some new vocabulary along the way.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In 1944, the United States Department of the Interior published *The Aleut Language* as part of the war effort, allowing World War II soldiers to understand the language of the Aleuts.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] This English–language project was based on Veniaminov's work.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In 1950, Knut Bergsland began an extensive study of Aleut, perhaps the most rigorous to date, culminating in the publication of a complete Aleut dictionary in 1994 and a descriptive grammar in 1997.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Bergsland's work would not have been possible without key Aleut collaborators, especially Atkan linguist Moses Dirks.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Michael Krauss, Jeff Leer, Michael Fortescue, and Jerrold Sadock have published articles about Aleut.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Alice Taff has worked on Aleut since the 1970s.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Her work constitutes the most detailed accounts of Aleut phonetics and phonology available.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Berge's work includes treatments of Aleut discourse structure and morphosyntax, and curricular materials for Aleut, including a conversational grammar of the Atkan dialect, co-authored with Moses Dirks.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Bering Island dialect and Mednyj Aleut language have been extensively studied by Soviet and Russian linguists: Georgy Menovshchikov, Yevgeny Golovko, Nikolay Vakhtin.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] A dictionary and a comprehensive grammar were published.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] In 2005, the parish of All Saints of North America Orthodox Church began to re-publish all historic Aleut language texts from 1840–1940.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Archpriest Paul Merculief (originally from the Pribilofs) of the Russian Orthodox Diocese of Alaska and the Alaska State Library Historical Collection generously contributed their linguistic skills to the restoration effort.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The historic Aleut texts are available in the parish's Aleut library.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Revitalization efforts are a recent development for the Aleut language and are mostly in the hands of the Aleuts themselves.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] The first evidence of the preservation of the language came in the form of written documentation at the hands of the Russian Orthodox Church missionaries.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] However, as the historical events and factors transpired, Aleut's falling out of favor has brought upon a necessity for action if the language is to survive much longer.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Linguistic experts have been reaching out to the Aleut community in attempts to record and document the language from the remaining speakers.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Such efforts amount to "100 hours of conversation, along with the transcription and translation in Aleut, that will be transferred to compact disks or DVDs".
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] If Aleut does go extinct, these records will allow linguists and descendants of the Aleutian people to pass on as much knowledge of the language as they can.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Efforts like this to save the language are being sponsored by universities and local community interest groups, like the Aleutian/Pribilof Islands Association Task Force for Language Revitalization, while government relations with the Aleut people are severely limited.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] Similarly to the native languages of California, the native languages of Alaska had been given little attention from the United States government.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] While linguists are working to record and document the language, the local Aleutian community groups are striving to preserve their language and culture by assisting the linguists and raising awareness of the Aleut population.
[src:chaplino-dialect/aleut-language] There is an Aleut course named *Unangam Qilinĝingin* on Memrise.
[src:chaplino-dialect/alutiiq-language] The ethnonyms of the Sugpiaq-Alutiiq are a predicament.
[src:chaplino-dialect/alutiiq-language] *Aleut*, *Alutiiq*, *Sugpiaq*, *Russian*, *Pacific Eskimo*, *Unegkuhmiut*, and *Chugach Eskimo* are among the terms that have been used to identify this group of Native people living on the Lower Kenai Peninsula of Alaska.
[src:chaplino-dialect/alutiiq-language] About 400 of the Alutiiq population of 3,000 still speak the Alutiiq language.
[src:chaplino-dialect/alutiiq-language] Alutiiq communities are currently in the process of revitalizing their language.
[src:chaplino-dialect/alutiiq-language] In 2010 the high school in Kodiak responded to requests from students and agreed to teach the Alutiiq language.
[src:chaplino-dialect/alutiiq-language] The Kodiak dialect of the language was spoken by only about 50 persons, all of them elderly, and the dialect was in danger of being lost entirely.
[src:chaplino-dialect/alutiiq-language] As of 2014, Alaska Pacific University in Anchorage is offering classes using the "Where Are Your Keys?" technique.
[src:chaplino-dialect/alutiiq-language] 2. [w] is an allophone of /ɣʷ/ syllable-finally and elsewhere.
[src:chaplino-dialect/alutiiq-language] Two consecutive identical consonants are pronounced either separately or as a geminate depending on dialect.
[src:chaplino-dialect/alutiiq-language] More consonants /ɾ~r, lʲ, rʲ/ are found in loanwords.
[src:chaplino-dialect/alutiiq-language] All vowels except /ə/ are considered full vowels and can be either short or long. /ə/ does not lengthen and does not occur in vowel clusters but may tend to be devoiced as [ə̥] next to other consonants.
[src:chaplino-dialect/alutiiq-language] After voiceless consonants, the voiceless nasals are written without h-.
[src:chaplino-dialect/be-cyrillic] The Cyrillic letters Be and Ve (В в) were both derived from the Greek letter Beta (Β β).
[src:chaplino-dialect/be-cyrillic] In the Early Cyrillic alphabet the name of the letter Be was бѹкꙑ (*buky*/буки), meaning "letter".
[src:chaplino-dialect/be-cyrillic] In the Cyrillic numeral system, the letter Be had no numeric value because the letter Ve inherited the Greek letter Beta's numeric value.
[src:chaplino-dialect/be-cyrillic] The Russian small letter б (*be*) is similar (but not identical) in shape to the digit 6.
[src:chaplino-dialect/be-cyrillic] Its lowercase form also somewhat resembles a lowercase letter B ("b"), the letter to which it corresponds in the Latin alphabet.
[src:chaplino-dialect/be-cyrillic] After all, the lowercase Latin letter B ("b") developed from scribal alterations to the capital letter B ("B"), just as б did from scribal alterations to the capital letter В ("Ve").
[src:chaplino-dialect/be-cyrillic] In Serbian and Macedonian the italic form is allowed to vary, but the regular should look like in other languages.
[src:chaplino-dialect/be-cyrillic] The cursive form of the lowercase letter Be resembles the lowercase Greek letter Delta (δ), but they are slightly different in their upper portions.
[src:chaplino-dialect/be-cyrillic] In Russian and Bulgarian, the letter Be generally represents the voiced bilabial plosive /b/, but word-finally or before a voiceless consonant, it also represents the voiceless [p].
[src:chaplino-dialect/be-cyrillic] Before a palatalizing vowel, it represents /bʲ/.
[src:chaplino-dialect/be-cyrillic] In Macedonian, the letter represents the sound /b/, but if it is in the final position of the word, it is pronounced as /p/, like in леб /lɛp/ ('bread').
[src:chaplino-dialect/be-cyrillic] In Mari, it may represent either /b/ or the voiced bilabial fricative /β/.
[src:chaplino-dialect/be-cyrillic] In Serbian, the letter represents the voiced bilabial plosive /b/, regardless of the position in the word.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Yupʼik, like all Eskimo languages, is polysynthetic and uses suffixation as primary means for word formation.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] There are a great number of derivational suffixes (termed *postbases*) that are used productively to form these polysynthetic words.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Yupʼik has predominantly ergative alignment: case marking follows the ergative pattern for the most part, but verb agreement can follow an ergative or an accusative pattern, depending on grammatical mood.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The language grammatically distinguishes three numbers: singular, dual, and plural.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] There is no marking of grammatical gender in the language, nor are there articles.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The Yup'ik language goes by various names.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Since it is a geographically central member of the Yupik languages and is spoken in Alaska, the language is often referred to as *Central Alaskan Yupik* (for example, in Miyaoka's 2012 grammar of the language).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The term *Yup'ik* [jupːik] is a common endonym, and is derived from /juɣ-piɣ/ "person-genuine".
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Yupʼik is spoken primarily in southwestern Alaska, from Norton Sound in the north to the Alaska Peninsula in the south, and from Lake Iliamna in the east to Nunivak Island in the west.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Yup'ik lies geographically central relative to the other members of the Yupik language family: Alutiiq ~ Sugpiaq is spoken to south and east, and Central Siberian Yupik is spoken to the west on St.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Lawrence Island Yupik* in the Alaskan context) and on the Chukotka peninsula, where Naukan Yupik is also spoken.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Yup'ik is bordered to the north by the more distantly related Iñupiaq language; the difference between Yupʼik and Iñupiaq is comparable to that of the difference between Spanish and French.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Of a total population of more than 23,000 people, more than 14,000 are speakers of the language.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Children still grow up speaking Yupʼik as their first language in 17 of 68 Yupʼik villages, those mainly located on the lower Kuskokwim River, on Nelson Island, and along the coast between the Kuskokwim River and Nelson Island.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The variety of Yup'ik spoken by the younger generations is being influenced strongly by English: it is less synthetic, has a reduced inventory of spatial demonstratives, and is lexically Anglicized.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Yup'ik is typically considered to have five dialects: **Norton Sound**, **General Central Yup'ik**, **Nunivak**, **Hooper Bay-Chevak**, and the extinct **Egegik** dialect.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] All extant dialects of the language are mutually intelligible, albeit with phonological and lexical differences that sometimes cause difficulty in cross-dialectal comprehension.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Lexical differences exist somewhat dramatically across dialects, in part due to a historical practice of name taboo.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Speakers may be reluctant to take on the lexicon of another dialect because they "often feel proud of their own dialects".
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The last of these, the Nunivak dialect (*Cupʼig*) is distinct and highly divergent from mainland Yupʼik dialects.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The only significant difference between Hooper Bay and Chevak dialects is the pronunciation of the initial *y-* [j] as *c-* [tʃ] in Chevak in some words: *Yupʼik* in Hooper Bay but *Cupʼik* in Chevak.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Even sub-dialects may differ with regard to pronunciation and lexicon.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The following table compares some words in two sub-dialects of General Central Yupʼik (*Yugtun*).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] A syllabary known as the Yugtun script was invented for the language by Uyaquq, a native speaker, in about 1900, although the language is now mostly written using the Latin script.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Early linguistic work in Central Yupʼik was done primarily by Russian Orthodox, then Jesuit and Moravian Church missionaries, leading to a modest tradition of literacy used in letter writing.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] In the 1960s, Irene Reed and others at the Alaska Native Language Center developed a modern writing system for the language.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Their work led to the establishment of the state's first bilingual school programs in four Yupʼik villages in the early 1970s.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Since then a wide variety of bilingual materials has been published, including Steven Jacobson's comprehensive dictionary of the language, his complete practical classroom grammar, and story collections and narratives by many others including a full novel by Anna Jacobson.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] While several different systems have been used to write Yupʼik, the most widely used orthography today is that adopted by the Alaska Native Language Center and exemplified in Jacobson's (1984) dictionary, Jacobson's (1995) learner's grammar, and Miyaoka's (2012) grammar.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The orthography is a Latin-script alphabet; the letters and digraphs used in alphabetical order are listed below, along with an indication of their associated phonemes in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The vowel qualities /a, i, u/ may occur long; these are written *aa*, *ii*, *uu* when vowel length is not a result of stress.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Consonants may also occur long (geminate), but their occurrence is often predictable by regular phonological rules, and so in these cases is not marked in the orthography.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Where long consonants occur unpredictably they are indicated with an apostrophe following consonant.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] For example, *Yupiaq* and *Yupʼik* both contain a geminate *p* (/pː/).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] In *Yupiaq* length is predictable and hence is not marked; in *Yupʼik* the length is not predictable and so must be indicated with the apostrophe.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] An apostrophe is also used to separate *n* from *g*, to distinguish *n'g* /nɣ/ from the digraph *ng* /ŋ/.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Apostrophes are also used between two consonants to indicate that voicing assimilation has not occurred (see below), and between two vowels to indicate the lack of gemination of a preceding consonant.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] A hyphen is used to separate a clitic from its host.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Yup'ik contrasts four vowel qualities: /a i u ə/.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The reduced vowel /ə/ always manifests phonetically short in duration, but the other three vowel qualities may occur phonetically short or long: [a aː i iː u uː].
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Phonetically long vowels come about when a full vowel (/a i u/) is lengthened by stress (see below), or when two single vowels are brought together across a morpheme boundary.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The effect is that while phonetic vowel length may yield a surface contrast between words, phonetic length is predictable and thus not phonemically contrastive.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The vowel qualities [e o] are allophones of /i u/, and are found preceding uvular consonants (such as [q] or [ʁ]) and preceding the low vowel [a].
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Yup'ik does not contrast voicing in stops, but has a wide range of fricatives that contrast in voicing.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The phoneme /l/ is not phonetically a fricative, but behaves as one phonologically in Yup'ik (in particular with regard to voicing alternations, where it alternates with [ɬ]; see below).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Contrasts between /s/ and /z/ and between /f/ and /v/ are rare, and the greater part of the voicing contrasts among fricatives is between the laterals /l/ and /ɬ/, the velars /x/ and /ɣ/, and the uvulars /χ/ and /ʁ/.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] For some speakers, there is also a voicing contrast among the nasal consonants, which is typologically somewhat rare.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Any consonant may occur as a geminate word-medially, and consonant length is contrastive.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The table above includes the allophones [χʷ], [ts], and [w].
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The voiceless labialized uvular fricative [χʷ] occurs only in some speech variants and does not contrast with its voiced counterpart /ʁʷ/.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The voiceless alveolar affricate [ts] is an allophone of /tʃ/ before the schwa vowel.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The voiced labiovelar approximant [w] is an allophone of /v/ that typically occurs between two full vowels, excepting when it occurs adjacent to an inflectional suffix.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] For example, /tʃali-vig-∅/ "work-place-ABS" is pronounced [tʃaliːwik] (orthographically, *calivik*), since /v/ occurs between two full vowels and it not adjacent to the inflectional suffix.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] With /tʃav-utə/ "oar" by contrast, since /-utə/ is an inflectional suffix, /v/ does not undergo the allophonic alternation: [tʃavun] (*cavun*).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] In Norton Sound, as well as some villages on the lower Yukon, /j/ tends to be pronounced as [z] when following a consonant, and geminate /jː/ as [zː].
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] For example, the word *angyaq* "boat" of General Central Yup'ik (GCY) is *angsaq* [aŋzaq] Norton Sound.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Conversely, in the Hooper Bay-Chevak (HBC) dialect, there is no /z/ phoneme, and /j/ is used in its place, such that GCY *qasgiq* [qazɣeq] is pronounced *qaygiq* [qajɣeq].
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] HBC does not have the [w] allophone of /v/, such that /v/ is pronounced [v] in all contexts, and there are no labialized uvular fricatives.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] In the Nunivak dialect, one finds /aː/ in place of GCY /ai/, such that GCY *cukaitut* "they are slow" is pronounced *cukaatut*, there is no word-final fortition of /x/ and /χ/ (see below), and word-initial /xʷ/ is pronounced [kʷ].
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] There are a variety of voicing assimilation processes (specifically, devoicing) that apply mostly predictably to continuant consonants (fricatives and nasals); these processes are not represented in the orthography.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Occasionally these assimilation processes do not apply, and in the orthography an apostrophe is written in the middle of the consonant cluster to indicate this: *at'nguq* is pronounced [atŋoq], not [atŋ̊oq].
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Fricatives are devoiced word-initially and word-finally.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Another common phonological alternation of Yup'ik is word-final fortition.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Among consonants, only the stops /t k q/, the nasals /m n ŋ/, and the fricative /χ/ may occur word-finally.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Any other fricative (and in many cases also /χ/) will become a plosive when it occurs at the end of a word.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] For example, *qayar-pak* "big kayak" is pronounced [qaja**χ**pak], while "kayak" alone is [qaja**q**]; the velar fricative becomes a stop word-finally.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Moreover, the [k] of *-pak* is only a stop by virtue of it being word-final: if another suffix is added, as in *qayar-pag-tun* "like a big kayak" a fricative is found in place of that stop: [qajaχpa**x**tun].
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The voiced velar consonants /ɣ ŋ/ are elided between single vowels, if the first is a full vowel: /tuma-ŋi/ is pronounced *tumai* [tumːai] (with geminate [mː] resulting from automatic gemination; see below).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Starting from the leftmost syllable in a word and moving rightward, syllables usually are grouped into units (termed "feet") containing two syllables each, and the second syllable of each foot is stressed.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] (However, feet in Yup'ik may also consist of a single syllable, which is almost always closed and must bear stress.) For example, in the word *pissuqatalliniluni* "apparently about to hunt", every second syllable (save the last) is stressed.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The most prominent of these (i.e., the syllable that has primary stress) is the rightmost of the stressed syllables.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The iambic stress system of Yup'ik results in predicable iambic lengthening, a processes that serves to increase the weight of the prominent syllable in a foot.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] When lengthening cannot apply, a variety of processes involving either elision or gemination apply to create a well-formed prosodic word.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Iambic lengthening is the process by which the second syllable in an iambic foot is made more prominent by lengthening the duration of the vowel in that syllable.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] In Yup'ik, a bisyllabic foot whose syllables each contain one phonologically single vowel will be pronounced with a long vowel in the second syllable.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Thus *pissuqatalliniluni* /pisuqataɬiniluni/ "apparently about to hunt" is pronounced [(pi.'suː)(qa.'taː)(ɬi.'niː)lu.ni].
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Following standard linguistic convention, parentheses here demarcate feet, periods represent the remaining syllable boundaries, and apostrophes occur before syllables that bear stress.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] In this word the second, fourth, and sixth syllables are pronounced with long vowels as a result of iambic lengthening.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Iambic lengthening does not apply to final syllables in a word.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Because the vowel /ə/ cannot occur long in Yup'ik, when a syllable whose nucleus is /ə/ is in line to receive stress, iambic lengthening cannot apply.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] In Norton Sound dialects, the consonant following /ə/ will geminate if that consonant is not part of a cluster.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] This also occurs outside of Norton Sound if the consonants before and after /ə/ are phonetically similar.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] For example, /tuməmi/ "on the footprint" is *not* pronounced *[(tu.'məː)mi], which would be expected by iambic lengthening, but rather is pronounced [(tu.'məm)mi], with gemination of the second /m/ to increase the weight of the second syllable.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] There are a variety of prosodic factors that cause stress to retract (move backward) to a syllable where it would not otherwise be expected, given the usual iambic stress pattern.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] (These processes do not apply, however, in the Norton Sound dialects.) The processes by which stress retracts under prosodically-conditioned factors are said to feature *regression* of stress in Miyaoka's (2012) grammar.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] When regression occurs, the syllable to which stress regresses constitutes a monosyllabic foot.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The first of these processes is related to the inability of /ə/ to occur long.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Outside of Norton Sound, if the consonants before and after /ə/ are phonetically dissimilar, /ə/ will elide, and stress will retract to a syllable whose nucleus is the vowel before the elided /ə/.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] For example, /nəqə-ni/ "his own fish" is not pronounced *[(nə.'qəː)ni], which would be expected by iambic lengthening, but rather is pronounced *neq'ni* [('nəq)ni], which features the elision of /ə/ and a monosyllabic foot.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Second, if the first syllable of a word is closed (ends in a consonant), this syllable constitutes a monosyllabic foot and receives stress.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Iambic footing continues left-to-right from the right edge of that foot.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] For example, *nerciqsugnarquq* "(s)he probably will eat" has the stress pattern [('nəχ)(tʃiq.'sux)naχ.qoq], with stress on the first and third syllables.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Another third prosodic factor that influences regressive is hiatus: the occurrence of adjacent vowels.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Yup'ik disallows hiatus at the boundaries between feet: any two consecutive vowels must be grouped within the same foot.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] If two vowels are adjacent, and the first of these *would* be at the right edge of a foot (and thus stressed) given the usual iambic footing, the stress retracts to a preceding syllable.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Without regressive accent, *Yupiaq* /jupiaq/ would be pronounced *[(ju.'piː)aq], but because of the ban on hiatus at foot boundaries, stress retracts to the initial syllable, and consonant gemination occurs to increase the weight of that initial syllable, resulting in [('jup)pi.aq].
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] This process is termed *automatic gemination* in Jacobson's (1995) grammar.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Yup'ik also disallows iambic feet that consist of a closed syllable followed by an open one, i.e. feet of the form CVC.'CV(ː), where C and V stand for "consonant" and "vowel" respectively.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] To avoid this type of foot, stress retracts: *cangatenrituten* /tʃaŋatənʁitutən/ has the stress pattern [(tʃa.'ŋaː)('tən)(ʁi.'tuː)tən] to avoid the iambic foot *(tən.'ʁiː) that would otherwise be expected.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Yup'ik has highly synthetic morphology: the number of morphemes within a word is very high.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The language is moreover agglutinative, meaning that affixation is the primary strategy for word formation, and that an affix, when added to a word, does not unpredictably affect the forms of neighboring affixes.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Because of the tendency to create very long verbs through suffixation, a Yupʼik verb often carries as much information as an English sentence, and word order is often quite free.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Three parts of speech are identified: nouns, verbs, and particles.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Because there are fewer parts of speech than in (e.g.) English, each category has a wider range of uses.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] For example, Yup'ik grammatical case fulfills the role that English prepositions do, and nominal derivational affixes or roots fulfill the role that English adjectives do.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] In descriptive work on Yup'ik, there are four regions within nouns and verbs that are commonly identified.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The first of these is often called the *stem* (equivalent to the notion of a root), which carries the core meaning of the word.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Following the stem come zero or more *postbases*, which are derivational modifiers that change the category of the word or augment its meaning.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] (Yup'ik does not have adjectives; nominal roots and postbases are used instead.) The third section is called an *ending*, which carries the inflectional categories of case (on nouns), grammatical mood (on verbs), person, and number.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Finally, optional *enclitics* may be added, which usually indicate "the speaker's attitude towards what he is saying such as questioning, hoping, reporting, etc." Orthographically, enclitics are separated from the rest of the word with a hyphen.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] However, since hyphens are already used in glosses to separate morphemes, there is potential for confusion as to whether a morpheme is a suffix or an enclitic, so in glosses the equals sign is used instead.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Because post-bases are derivational morphemes, and thus can change the part of speech of a word, many verbs are built from noun stems, and vice versa.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] For example, **neqe-ngqer-tua** "I have fish" is a verb, despite the fact that **neqe-** "fish" is a noun; the postbase **-ngqerr** "have" makes the resulting word a verb.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] These changes in grammatical category can apply iteratively, such that over the course of word formation, a word may become a noun, then a verb, then back to a noun, and so on.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The conjugation of Yup'ik verbs involves obligatory marking of grammatical mood and agreement.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Yup'ik has a great number of grammatical moods.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The moods can be categorized according to whether the clause in which they are found is independent or subordinate.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] There are four so-called *independent moods*: the indicative, optative, interrogative, and participial; these typically are found on the main verbs of independent clauses.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Yupʼik also has ten *connective moods,* which occur on the verbs of adverbial clauses; the connective moods are the Yup'ik equivalent of many subordinating conjunctions of English, and are often translated as 'because', 'although', 'if' and 'while'.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] In addition to the connective moods listed above, there are five so-called "quasi-connective" moods.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Though these are adverbial adjuncts to main clauses and thus are similar in function to the connective moods, they inflect like nominals (they inflect with case, not agreement).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Yup'ik has a rich system of agreement on verbs.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Up to two nominal arguments may be cross-referenced (intransitive verbs agree with their sole argument, and transitive verbs agree with both arguments).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Three numbers (singular, dual, and plural) are distinguished, as well as at least three persons (first, second, and third).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The third person is unmarked when cross-referencing subjects, and the verbs of dependent clauses may have two types of third person forms depending on whether some argument is co-refers with the subject of the verb in the independent clause (see "Co-reference across clauses" below).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] To the extent that subject and object agreement markers are not fusional, subject agreement linearly precedes object agreement.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Agreement markers vary in form depending on the grammatical mood of the verb.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] In (1), the 1SG>3SG agreement marker is *-qa* because the verb is in the indicative mood, while in (2) the agreement marker is *-ku* due to verb being in the optative mood.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The participial and indicative share a set of agreement markers, and all the connective moods likewise share a common set (which is shared also with some possessed nouns).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The form of 3rd-person agreement in dependent clauses may vary depending on whether that 3rd-person argument is the same referent as, or a different referent than, a 3rd-person subject of the independent clause.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] In some descriptive work on the language, when the subject of the independent clause is co-referential with the relevant argument in the dependent clause, the agreement in the dependent clause is said to reflect a "fourth" or a "reflexive third" person.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Some grammatical moods do not have associated agreement markers that contrast these two types of third person.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Some researchers have argued that the contrast in (3-4) exemplifies a type of switch-reference, though McKenzie (2015) claims Yup'ik does not have the true characteristics of switch-reference, and that the Yup'ik system is better understood in terms of obviation or long-distance anaphora.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Yup'ik nouns inflect for number, case, and show agreement with the person and number of a possessor if present.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The morphosyntactic alignment of Yupʼik is ergative-absolutive, meaning that subjects of intransitive verbs bear the same grammatical case (the absolutive) as the objects of transitive verbs, while the subjects of transitive verbs have a different case (the ergative).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] For example, the sentence *Angyaq tak'uq* ("The boat is long") features an intransitive verb, and the subject (*angyaq*, "the boat") is in the absolutive case.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] By comparison, in the sentence *Angyaq kiputaa* ("He buys the boat"), the verb is transitive, and it is now the object (*angyaq*, "the boat") that bears the absolutive.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] This contrasts with nominative-accusative languages like English, where the subjects of intransitives and transitives are identical in form ("**He** slept", "**He** ate the bread"), while the objects of transitives have a different case ("The moose saw **him**").
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The forms of these grammatical cases are variable, depending on the grammatical person and number of the head noun as well as the person and number of its possessor (if there is one).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Possessed nouns, like all other nouns, inflect for number and case, but also show person and number agreement with their possessor.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] For example, consider a few forms of *saskaq* "cup".
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The two leftmost nouns below are unpossessed, but the third is marked for a first person singular possessor *-ka* (pronounced in this case as *-qa* after assimilating to a uvular place of articulation).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The final example marks plural number for both the noun itself and its possessor.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Yup'ik has considerably more freedom of word order than English does.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] In English, the word order of subjects and objects with respect to a verb reflects the thematic roles of the subject and object.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] In Yupʼik, word order is freer because the rich inflectional system often serves to unambiguously identify thematic relations without recourse to word order.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] These Yup'ik sentences both mean "the dog bit the preacher", for instance.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The word order varies between these sentences, but the fact that *qimugtem* ("dog") is marked with ergative case (*-m*) is sufficient to identify it as the thematic agent.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Despite the greater freedom of word order, there seems to be a general preference for Subject-Object-Verb (SOV) order (though VSO is also common, and pragmatic factors also play a significant role).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] This can be observed in circumstances where the inflectional system will not unambiguously determine which noun is the agent and which is the theme.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] In cases like this, the SOV preference comes into play, and the sentence is most readily interpreted as "the teachers like the children".
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Yup'ik has a rich system of spatial deixis.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] That is, many of the spatial properties of things and events are linguistically encoded in great detail; this holds true for demonstrative pronouns (like English "this one", "that one") as well as spatial adverbs ("here", "there").
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] There are twelve categories that define the orientation of a thing or event with respect to the *environment*.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] To illustrate, the spatial demonstrative roots of Yup'ik (which are then inflected for case and number) are presented in the following table from Miyaoka (2012).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Note that Classes I and II lack distal forms due to an inherently non-distal meaning (these forms only locate things that are near to the speaker/hearer).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Class III is purely anaphoric, and thus only has a distal form.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Small changes have been made towards teaching Yupʼik to the native Alaskan Yupʼiks.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] In 1972, the Alaska State Legislature passed legislation mandating that if "a [school is attended] by at least 15 pupils whose primary language is other than English, [then the school] shall have at least one teacher who is fluent in the native language".
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] However, "the statute addressed all languages other than English, and thus expanded bilingualism equally to immigrant languages," meaning that although the statute welcomed non-English languages into schools, its primary "aim" was to "promote English proficiency", not to keep Yupʼik alive.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] This proposal for the Alaska Native Language Policy comes three years after Steven A.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] In 2018, Anchorage's first Yup'ik immersion program was launched at College Gate Elementary.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] Yup'ik language courses are offered at the University of Alaska Anchorage and the University of Alaska Fairbanks.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-alaskan-yupʼik] The latter also offers Bachelor's degrees in Yupʼik Language and Culture, as well as associate degrees in Native Language Education with a concentration in Yupʼik, and certificates in Yupʼik Language Proficiency.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] In the United States, the Alaska Native Language Center identified about 400–750 Yupigestun speakers, considering "dormant speakers" who understand but cannot converse.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] In Russia in 2021, 172 people indicated that they speak the language, while only 92 of them use it in everyday life.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Thus, the total number of speakers is no more than 550–900 people.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Siberian Yupik has two dialects: **Chaplino (Chaplinski) Yupik** (Uŋazigmit) is spoken on the shores of Chukotka Autonomous Okrug in the Russian Far North, and **St.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Lawrence Island Yupik** (Sivuqaghmiistun) is spoken on St.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Chaplino, or *Uŋazigmit*, is the largest Yupik language of Siberia (the second one is Naukan Yupik), and is named after the settlement of Уӈазиӄ (Ungaziq; Chaplino or *Old Chaplino* in Russian).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] The word *Ungazighmii* / Уңазиӷмӣ [uŋaʑiʁmiː] (plural *Ungazighmiit* / Уңазиӷмӣт [uŋaʑiʁmiːt]) means "Ungaziq inhabitant(s)".
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] People speaking this language live in several settlements in the southeastern Chukchi Peninsula (including Novoye Chaplino, Provideniya, and Sireniki), Uelkal, Wrangel Island, and Anadyr.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] The majority of Chaplino Yupik speakers live in the villages of Novoye Chaplino and Sireniki.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] In another terminology, these people speak Chaplino, and Ungazighmiit people speak one of its dialects, along with other dialects spoken by Avatmit, Imtugmit, Kigwagmit, which can be divided further into even smaller dialects.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Lawrence Island Yupik, is believed to be an offspring of Chaplino with only minor phonetic, phonological, morphological, syntactical and lexical differences, and the two dialects are virtually identical.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Unlike the Central Alaskan Yupik languages, Siberian Yupik has a series of retroflex fricatives, more similar to the Alaskan Inuit dialects.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Morphosyntax is the study of grammatical categories or linguistic units that have both morphological and syntactic properties.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Central Siberian Yupik’s structure most resembles this category.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] In addition, CSY can be described as using both internal and external syntax.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Internal syntax is used here to describe the way that postbases are added to a base or added to one another, contrasted with external syntax, which refers to the order of independent words.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Central Siberian Yupik is a polysynthetic language, meaning it is made up of long, structured words containing many separate meaningful parts (morphemes).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] In fact, a single word can be an entire sentence.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] CSY is also an ergative-absolutive language, in contrast to the nominative-accusative structure of English and many Indo-European languages.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Generally, the "base" or "stem" contains the root meaning of the word, while the "postbases", which are suffixing morphemes, provide additional components of the sentence (see example above).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] As shown, postbases include items with adjectival and verbal qualities, among other elements.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] The "ending" (Woodbury’s term) is an inflectional suffix to the right of the postbase that contains grammatical information such as number, person, case, or mood.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Enclitics are bound suffixes that follow the inflectional ending of a word.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] An attached enclitic affects the meaning of the entire sentence, not just the element to which it is attached.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] The base forms the lexical core of the word and belongs to one of three main classes: noun bases, verb bases and particle bases.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Noun endings indicate number (singular, dual, or plural), case, and whether or not the noun is possessed.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] If the noun is possessed, the ending indicates the number and person of the possessor.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] As in other ergative-absolutive languages, absolutive case is used to mark nouns that are generally the subjects of intransitive verbs or the objects of transitive verbs.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Ergative case identifies nouns as a subject of a transitive verb and acts as the genitive form in ergative-absolutive languages.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] The ablative case is used to indicate the agent in passive sentences, or the instrument, manner, or place of the action described by the verb.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] The endings of the locative and terminative cases are the same as those of the ablative case except that the locative case has *-mi* and *-ni* and the terminative case has *-mun* and *-nun* in place of the *-meng* and *-neng* at the end of the ablative case endings.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] In grammar, the prolative case, also called the vialis case, is a grammatical case of a noun or pronoun that expresses motion by the referent of the noun it marks.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Equative is a case that expresses the standard of comparison of equal values.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Derivation is accomplished in CSY by attaching suffixes called postbases.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Productivity in the context of CSY is defined as the free addition of a postbase to any base without an unpredictable semantic result; non-productivity implies that said postbases cannot combine freely but are limited to attaching to only a particular set of bases.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Postbases are either nominal or verbal and select nominal or verbal bases or expanded bases to attach to (an expanded base is a base followed by one or more postbases).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] It is estimated that CSY has approximately 547 postbases: 75 NN, 55 NV, 30 VN, and 387 VV.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] It appears that in CSY the large majority of NN, NV, and VN postbases are productive; for the VV postbases, there are approximately 190 non-productive ones and 197 productive ones.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] There are no clear morphological position classes in CSY.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] A position class is the organization of morphemes or a morpheme class into a linear ordering with no apparent connection to syntactic, semantic, or phonological representation.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] In the example below, it is semantic restrictions that dictate the order.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] ‘Also, it turns out she/he wanted to go eat it, but. . .’.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Some postbases can be used recursively, as in the example below.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] ‘Hei asked himj to go ask himk to come in’.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Recursion can also be used for emphasis.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] There is variability in postbase ordering with no change in semantic outcome.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Abbreviations: V, verb; PST, past tense; FRUSTR, frustrative (‘but . . ., in vain’); INFER, inferential evidential (often translatable as ‘it turns out’); INDIC, indicative; 3S3S, third-person subject acting on third-person object): (de Reuse 2006) Note: postbases noted in bold.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Note: there is a general rule in CSY of semantic scope in which the rightmost postbase will have scope over the left.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] However, there are many exceptions, as in the example above.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Following are a brief list and description of enclitics in CSY.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] The table is recreated from de Reuse (1988).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Note: the ‘position’ references above refer to the position of the postbase following the main base.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Naukan, or Nuvuqaghmiistun, the second largest Yupik language spoken in Chukotka, is spoken in settlements including Uelen, Lorino, Lavrentiya, and Provideniya.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Additionally, the Sireniki Eskimo language, locally called Uqeghllistun, was an Eskimo language once spoken in Chukotka.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Sometimes it is classified as not belonging to the Yupik branch at all, thus forming (by itself) a stand-alone third branch of the Eskimo languages (alongside Inuit and Yupik).
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Its peculiarities may be the result of a supposed long isolation from other Eskimo groups in the past.
[src:chaplino-dialect/central-siberian-yupik-language] Sireniki became extinct in early January 1997.
[src:chaplino-dialect/chaplino-dialect] The Chaplino dialect is named after the village of Chaplino (also known as "*Old Chaplino*"; native name is "Уӈазиӄ" (Uŋaziq), from *уӈаӄ* "whisker" + suffix *-зиӄ/-сиӄ*).
[src:chaplino-dialect/chaplino-dialect] The Chaplino dialect is spoken by the majority of Russian Yuits.
[src:chaplino-dialect/chaplino-dialect] The Chaplino dialect is close in lexicon and grammar to that of the St.
[src:chaplino-dialect/chaplino-dialect] Lawrence Island Yupik dialect (*"Sivuqaghmiistun"*).
